To further support the formation of hybridized framework, the remained poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB), which didn’t decompose with acid, was extracted and further treated with alkaline to form pyridine groups. FTIR spectroscopy of this sample was conducted. One can imagine that if copolymerization actually occurs, the pyridine groups should be preserved in the framework of this sample. From the spectra (Fig. 3
                        ), the absorption band at 1617 cm−1, which was attributed to the vibration of CN after coordination, shift to 1599 cm−1. The latter absorption band was attributed to the vibration of CN on pristine pyridine. Above result indicated the preserve of pyridine group, thus proving that the pyridine and derived coordination bonds were actually introduced into the hybridized framework, and the copolymerization took place. The morphology of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) was observed by SEM. SEM images show that poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) basically have the morphology of nanosheets like poly(ZnVP2) (Fig. 4
                        ). However, the size of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) nanosheets is commonly smaller than that of poly(ZnVP2). One possible explanation for this is that the introduction of covalent framework inhibits the assembly dominated by coordination structure. TEM image further verifies the nanosheet morphology of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) (Fig. 4c). The thickness of the nanosheets appears to be much small.

Porous properties of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) was characterized by nitrogen absorption experiments at 77 K. In identical with the absorption curve of poly(ZnVP2), a type H3 hysteresis loop was seen at high P/P0
                        , which reflected the characteristic of a layered mesoporous structure (Fig. 5
                        ). Such layered structure is also observed from SEM images. However, compared with poly(ZnVP2), a steep increasing curve in a low p/p0 range of 0–0.1 is not seen for poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB), indicating that almost no micropores exist in poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB). The micropores are generally originated from the big and rigid skeleton. The moieties derived from DVB are great small. Thus, the incorporation of DVB-derived framework largely inhibits the generation of micropores. The calculated BET area of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) was 89.2 m2 g−1, which was lower than that of poly(ZnVP2).

Poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) also exhibited sensing ability toward Cu2+ ions. The sensitivity of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) toward Cu2+ detection was evaluated by its real-time fluorescence response. As shown in Fig. 6
                        a, upon the addition of Cu2+, the fluorescence emission of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) was clearly quenched. The quenching efficiency was continually decreased with increasing the concentration of Cu2+ to ∼ 100 ppm (Fig. 6b). When further increasing the concentration, the quenching efficiency was kept almost the same, indicating that the adsorption of Cu2+ reached the maxima. The inset image in Fig. 6b showed the linear range (2∼10 ppm) of the calibration curve. From the curve, the detection limit for Cu2+ in aqueous solution was determined as 128 ppb using the equation LOD = 3 × S.D./k, where k represents the slope of the curve equation, and S.D. is the standard deviation for F0 (the fluorescence intensity of poly (ZnVP2) in the absence of Cu2+). This detection limit is greatly below the limit for the copper in the drinking water (1.3 ppm), thus representing a good sensitivity toward the Cu2+ detection. Moreover, from comparing the detection limit of several absorbents for Cu2+ ion (Table 1
                        ), poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) has comparable detection limit with these absorbents.

To verify the selectivity of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) for the practical detection of Cu2+, the competition experiments were further conducted. As shown in Fig. 8
                        a, when other cations were added in Cu2+ aqueous solution, the quenching efficiency was almost not been affected. Thus, neither of the competitive metal ions showed an appreciable effect on the Cu2+ detection. Identical result was also found for the mixture with multiple metal ions (Cu2+, Ni2+ and Zn2+). Except as fluorimetric sensor, poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) could also be used as naked-eye sensor. From Fig. 8b, poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) exhibited rapid and visual color change to blue in about 3 min after Cu2+ uptake. This colour change started appearing at concentrations of Cu2+ as low as 20 μM. This phenomenon was not observed for other cations. The competition experiments further indicated that competitive metal ions hardly affected the chromic properties (Fig. 8b). Moreover, from Fig. 2, poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) and poly(ZnVP2) exhibited colour change to red at pH > 9, thus showing pH responsive property. To gain further insights into the selectivity of poly(ZnVP2-co-DVB) for Cu2+ detection, the interaction of poly(ZnVP2) with Cu2+ was studied. FTIR spectra (Fig. 9
                        ) showed that after the uptake of Cu2+, the absorption band of coordinated bonds at 1617 cm−1 shifted to 1615 cm−1. This result indicated the substitution of Zn2+ in poly(ZnVP2) by Cu2+ via coordination reaction. New adsorption band appearred at 1600 cm-1, indicating that portions of coordination bonds transferred to pyridine hydrochloride owing to the acidic environment. Meanwhile, no fluorescence was observed for poly (CuVP2), thus resulting in the quench of fluorescence. The selective uptake of Cu2+ in poly(ZnVP2) is possibly correlated to the pre-coordination of pyridine groups with Zn2+, which greatly alter the affinity of pyridine groups and may prevents the uptake of most of other metal ions.
